  "deep_dive": {
    "full_text": "Confirmed facts: Nifty fell 0.66% to 24,052.05 and Sensex declined 0.72% to 77,054.94. Twelve of 16 major sectors fell; banks and financial services lost about 1.1%, autos 1.6%, midcaps 0.4% and smallcaps 1.0%. The rupee weakened to about 96.2375 per dollar, with Reuters reporting likely RBI intervention. India's 10-year yield rose by roughly 6 basis points to around 6.79%-6.81%. Brent reached about $86-$87 as US-Iran tensions and Strait of Hormuz risks escalated. The US 10-year yield was around 4.63%; Dow fell 0.3% and Nasdaq 1.6% in the prior session, while Nikkei rose about 0.7%, Hang Seng 0.6% and STOXX 600 fell 0.7%. Reasoned interpretation: The decline was an oil-and-inflation risk-off move. Higher crude weakened the rupee, lifted inflation and yield concerns, and hurt rate-sensitive and fuel-sensitive sectors. Nifty holding near 24,000 limits immediate technical damage, but another crude spike could deepen the correction.",
    "summary_takeaway": "Crude oil is the decisive variable: below $84 can support a rebound, while a move toward $90 would deepen pressure on India-sensitive assets."
